  "market_context": "EUR/USD on the daily chart in mid-2023 showing a bearish displacement range. Price retraces back up into a daily OTE zone, and the analyst drops down to the hourly to observe the same logic recursively forming new OTE ranges after each displacement.",
  "key_observation": "After a displacement move and a retracement into OTE, each new swing creates another displacement range whose own OTE can be marked. This cascading OTE structure repeats fractally across daily, hourly, and lower time frames, often aligning with breakers and fair value gaps for confluence.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the EUR/USD daily chart, identify the bearish displacement range and draw a Fibonacci with 0.5, 0.62, 0.705, and 0.79 OTE levels.",
    "Step 2: Observe that price retraces back up into the daily OTE zone before moving lower, confirming the OTE reaction.",
    "Step 3: Drop to the hourly chart and mark out the same daily displacement range, noting that price retraces into the hourly OTE and fills an hourly fair value gap.",
    "Step 4: Wait for hourly displacement lower, then use the most recent high that produced a new low to draw a fresh OTE on the hourly range.",
    "Step 5: As price extends lower and makes new lows, extend the OTE downward and watch for retracements back into each new OTE.",
    "Step 6: Identify a breaker forming inside the OTE zone for added confluence and watch the reaction when price returns to that area.",
    "Step 7: Confirm a clean reaction off the breaker plus OTE confluence, demonstrating cascading OTE usage across time frames."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price reacted cleanly off the breaker and OTE confluence on the hourly chart, validating the cascading OTE approach.",
  "lessons": "OTE logic is fractal: each displacement creates a new range whose OTE can be marked on the next lower time frame. Stacking OTE with breakers or fair value gaps provides high-confluence entries that align HTF bias with LTF execution.",
